-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks Report: Cal Bank, Ghana Oil Are Active in Trading
-- B y   J a s o n   M c L u r e
-- 2011-02-07T17:10:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-07/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-report-cal-bank-ghana-oil-are-active-in-trading.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index snapped three days of increases, slipping 0.9 percent to
close at 1,050.35 by 3 p.m. in Accra.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index retreated for a second day, losing
0.2 percent to close at 2,023.56 by 1:30 p.m. in  Port Louis .
Kenya’s All-Share Index lost 0.1 percent to close at 78.48 by 3
p.m. in Nairobi, a second day of declines. The Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index fell for a third day, dropping 0.4
percent to 26,669.91 by the 2:30 p.m. close, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg. Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index 
rallied for a fifth day, adding 0.3 percent to 921.66 by the 5
p.m. close in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    CAL Bank Ltd . (CAL GN), a Ghanaian lender, dropped the most
since June 3, retreating 4 pesewas, or 10 percent, to 35
pesewas. The stock’s recommendation was reduced to
“accumulate” from “buy” by African Alliance.  Ghana Oil Co. (GOIL GN), which runs a network of gasoline
stations in the West African nation, dropped 1 pesewa, or 3
percent, to 32 pesewas. Oil declined for a third day on
skepticism that a rebounding U.S. economy will reduce surplus
inventories in the world’s biggest oil-consuming country.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jason McLure in Accra on 
 jmclure@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
